"US natural gas futures skyrocketed 10% to around $7/MMBtu, paring much of their losses from an unseasonal slump at the beginning of December, amid forecasts for much colder weather and higher heating demand than previously expected. Frigid temperatures and heavy precipitation on the West Coast have fueled natural gas demand at a time when storage inventories are below average. Meanwhile, the Freeport LNG export plant in Texas, forced to go offline in June following a fire, expects to begin bringing operations back online by year's end, in another delay due to pending regulatory approval. Still, prices remain subdued for this time of the year, as milder weather in most of October and November delayed the winter heating season while record production levels added to the bearish sentiment. EIA reported that US production of dry natural gas, used primarily in homes and businesses for heating, cooking, and electricity, is set to break an annual record of 98.0 Bcf/d in 2022."

This question deals only with the US price for natural gas. There will continue to be regional price differences, but to the extent that LNG capacity growth can move gas around the world we are converging on a global price. Due to the Ukraine War, Europe has become a major market for US LNG. High prices for gas in Europe pulled cargoes from Asia, and COVID shutdowns reduced demand in China. European gas stores are at unusually high levels for this time of year, and prices have fallen. See https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2022-10-24/european-gas-futures-dip-below-100-with-bout-of-mild-weather?sref=x7nYEkiY, and https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2022-10-25/too-much-gas-the-unexpected-twist-in-europe-s-energy-crisis?sref=x7nYEkiY.

Europe has increased its storage of natural gas faster than had been anticipated. It currently stands at 89% of capacity. See https://www.statista.com/statistics/1294025/quarterly-gas-in-storage-in-the-european-union/.

The price of US natural gas dropped by about a third in June after an LNG export hub in Houston, TX was shut down. In July the price resumed its climb.

It is most likely that gas prices will continue to rise. Typically gas prices are seasonal, yet we have seen a dramatic spike persistent throughout the summer months of the northern hemisphere. Gas prices are set by the international market, and the US established a policy that stopped the exportation of gas on federal land, which accounts for approximately 25% of the total gas supplied by the US (which ranks #1 in the entire world for oil). The demand in the summer has shown to be more than sustainable during the summer months, so it would be natural to assume a higher price in the winter, correct? A refutation to this position would be favorable action by the US government on gas prices, regardless of the bills that were passed within the last two years which are a key contributing factor to prices today. These include corporate deals or the presidency exercising emergency powers and nationalizing the gas (and oil, even though this question is specific to gas) industry. This sounds extreme but nonetheless is a trajectory that must be accounted for.

Part of the rise of the US natural gas spot price was tied to increased demand in Europe for liquified natural gas (LNG, gas that can be shipped out of the US) as a replacement for Russian gas. There has been a fire at a major LNG export facility (https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/stock-market-today-dow-jones-bitcoin-fed-rates-06-14-2022/card/natural-gas-prices-plunge-18-on-extended-outage-at-texas-lng-facility-PvSupRh4LhcTTHMom6Bs), which will reduce the ability to export natural gas from the US to Europe, increasing the amount of gas available to the US market, which has caused a drop in price recently. Although the Texas facility won't be back up and running for a while, domestic demand for gas seems to be higher than average, and other facilities could try to make up some of the lost exports from the Texas facility as there is clearly a lot of money to be made. As a result, I still expect prices to rise by the end of the year, especially if the Texas facility is operational again by then.
